The “satanic D&D craze”

The panic around Dungeons & Dragons in the late 1970s and 1980s wasn’t because there was evidence the game was causing occult practices. Historians generally describe it as part of the broader Satanic Panic—a period when many people feared hidden cults, ritual abuse, and media influences without reliable evidence supporting those fears.

Several factors reinforced one another:

* Fantasy themes involving demons, magic, and mythology.
* Tragic events that were incorrectly linked to the game.
* Media amplification.
* Parents encountering a new hobby they didn’t understand.
* Broader cultural anxiety about changing values and youth culture.

In Pantheon terms, you could describe this as a narrative feedback loop: uncertainty + unfamiliar symbols + social amplification produced a compelling story that spread more effectively than careful evidence.

